{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17566926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17566926"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:51:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:51:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18905"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18905","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18905"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.01,0.25,0.72,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11638"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80124"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11638"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18905"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65401"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"5678"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11349"},{"type":"tags","id":"11353"},{"type":"tags","id":"12867"},{"type":"tags","id":"12918"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27378"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36381"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80124"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with multiple injuries following a motor vehicle accident. She is a well-known social media influencer. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears stable with vital signs within normal limits. She has multiple superficial lacerations to her face and arms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile providing care, you overhear several staff members discussing posting about the incident on social media. One staff member suggests that since no patient identifying information would be included, it would be acceptable to share details about the case.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate response to the staff members?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Posting is acceptable if images are not included","Posting is acceptable if no names are mentioned","Posting is acceptable if the patient consents","Posting is never acceptable in this situation","Posting is acceptable after discharge"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario addresses the fundamental principles of patient privacy and confidentiality in healthcare. Healthcare workers have both ethical and legal obligations to maintain patient confidentiality, regardless of the patient\u0027s public profile or the circumstances of their presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosting is never acceptable in this situation\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct response. Even without explicitly identifying information, sharing details about a patient\u0027s care on social media is a breach of confidentiality. The unique circumstances of the case (a well-known person in a motor vehicle accident) could make the patient identifiable even without naming them directly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosting is acceptable if no names are mentioned\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The absence of a name does not guarantee anonymity, especially in cases involving public figures or unique circumstances. Other details could make the patient identifiable to the community.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosting is acceptable if the patient consents\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While patient consent is important, healthcare workers should maintain professional boundaries and avoid sharing patient information on social media, even with consent. This maintains the integrity of the therapeutic relationship.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosting is acceptable after discharge\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The duty of confidentiality extends indefinitely, not just during the period of care. Information learned during the course of providing healthcare remains confidential even after the therapeutic relationship ends.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosting is acceptable if images are not included\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The absence of images does not make it acceptable to share patient information. Written descriptions can be just as identifying as images and still constitute a breach of confidentiality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHealthcare workers should remember that privacy laws and professional codes of conduct exist to protect patient confidentiality and maintain public trust in the healthcare system. Information about patients should only be shared with those directly involved in their care, through appropriate clinical channels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Patient information should only be shared with those directly involved in their care unless explicit consent is obtained.","Social media posts about patients, even without identifying details, may breach privacy and confidentiality.","Healthcare workers have an ethical and legal obligation to maintain patient confidentiality."],"references":["Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65401"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18905"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65401"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-17T13:21:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-17T13:23:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11638"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80124"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddd1\u200d\u2696\ufe0f","name":"Medicolegal","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","sy